DESCRIPTION:Presenter:Atibhav Chaudhry\n\nSupervisors:Rui Zhou\, Benjamin 
 Avanzi\, Jan Dhaene (KUL) and Katrien Antonio (KUL)\n\nTitle:On Modelling 
 Lifetimes\, Sharing Risk\, and Valuing Promises: Essays in Actuarial Scien
 ce\n\nDay/Time:Thursday 29 January 2026\, 9 - 10pm Australian Eastern Dayl
 ight Time Time (AEDT)\n\nMicrosoft Teams Link:https://teams.microsoft.com/
 l/meetup-join/19%3ameeting_ZTY2NGNkNWQtZTkxMi00NjQzLWE0ZDgtZjE0ODU4ZjViZDd
 k%40thread.v2/0?context=%7b%22Tid%22%3a%223973589b-9e40-4eb5-800e-b0b6383d
 1621%22%2c%22Oid%22%3a%224635721d-9028-4653-b4cb-4998f22fb087%22%7d\n\nAbs
 tract:\n\nChapter 1: “Modelling mortality dependence with time series vi
 ne copulas”\n\nWe propose time series vine copulas as a unified framewor
 k for modelling both serial and cross-sectional mortality dependence acros
 s multiple populations. Unlike VAR and ARIMA-copula approaches\, which imp
 ose linearity or model dependence in separate steps\, time series vine cop
 ulas allow flexible yet parsimonious joint dependence structures. Using mo
 rtality data from four populations\, we show that S-vines and their specia
 l cases (D-vines\, M-vines\, and stationary COPAR models) outperform exist
 ing methods in fitting and forecasting accuracy. We further demonstrate th
 at model choice can materially affect longevity bond pricing\, highlightin
 g the practical relevance of flexible dependence modelling.\n\nChapter 2: 
 “Compensation-based risk-sharing”\n\nThis chapter studies the mathemat
 ical problem of allocating payouts (compensations) in an endowment conting
 ency fund using a risk-sharing rule that satisfies full allocation. Beside
 s the participants\, an administrator manages the fund by collecting ex-an
 te contributions to establish the fund and distributing ex-post payouts to
  members. Two types of administrators are considered. An ‘active’ admi
 nistrator both invests in the fund and receives the payout of the fund whe
 n no participant receives a payout. A ‘passive’ administrator performs
  only administrative tasks and neither invests in nor receives a payout fr
 om the fund. We analyze the actuarial fairness of both compensation-based 
 risk-sharing schemes and provide general conditions under which fairness i
 s achieved. The results extend earlier work by Denuit and Robert (2025) an
 d Dhaene and Milevsky (2024)\, who focused on payouts based on Bernoulli d
 istributions\, by allowing for general non-negative loss distributions.\n\
 nChapter 3: “Information-constrained fair dynamic valuation of hybrid in
 surance liabilities”\n\nWe propose a discrete-time\, multi-period valuat
 ion framework for hybrid insurance claims that embeds three nested informa
 tion filtrations\, capturing asset-price risk\, systematic risk\, and poli
 cyholder-specific risk. The framework enforces a no-insider-trading requir
 ement and supports valuations that are simultaneously market-consistent\, 
 model-consistent\, and time-consistent. We show that\, in a multi-period s
 etting\, the three-step hedge-based valuations of Linders (2023) and an ad
 apted version of the two-step market evaluations of Pelsser and Stadje (20
 14) coincide with the class of fair dynamic valuations\, thereby unifying 
 these approaches within a filtration-sensitive framework.
